cjk_all: حريري المقامات. Incipit: قال الشيخ الرئيس ابو محمد القاسم بن علي بن محمد بن عثمان الحريري البصري رحمه الله تعالى ورضي عنه اللهم انا نحمدك على ما علمت من البيان والهمت من التبيان ... [2ب] ... وبعد قد جرى ببعض اندية الادب الذي ركدت في هذا العصرِ ريحه Explicit: فقال اجعل الموت [243ب] نصب عينك وهذا فراق بيني وبينك فودعته وعبراتي تتحدرن من الماقي وزفراتي تتصعدن من التراقي وكانت هذه خاتمة التلاقي قال الشيخ الرئيس ابو محمد القاسم بن علي ادام الله علوّه هذه اخر المقامات التي انشاتها بالاغترار وامليتها بلسان الاضطرار وقد الجئت الى ان ارصدتها للاستعراض وناديت عليها في سوق الاعتراض هذا مع معرفتي بانّها من سقط المتاع ... ولكن كان ذلك في الكتاب مسطورا وانا استغفر الله مما اودعتها [244أ] من اباطيل اللغو واضاليل اللهو واسترشده الى ما يعصم من السهو ... وولي الخيرات في الدنيا والاخرة والحمد لله رب العالمين وصلى الله على سيدنا محمد خاتم النبيين وعلى اله الطاهرين واصحابه المنتخبين وسلم الله تسليمًا الى يوم الدين امين والحمد به ربى

notes_index: Copied A.H. 936 [A.D. 1530] by ʻAbd al-Raḥmān ibn Aḥmad ibn Muḥammad ibn Aḥmad ibn Majd al-Dīn [?].
Numb. fols. 400; 26 x 17.4 cm.; written surface 21 x 12.4 cm.; 17 lines to page; on glazed Arabic paper; in naskhi; with catchwords; entries in red; with illuminations.
Volumes one and two of a work on ḥanafite law. The whole work is in ten volumes.
Beg.: بسم الله ... اما بعد فان من اشرف الامور وافضل

Colophon: وکان الفراغ من نسخ هذا الجزء في الىوم المبارك ىوم الخمىس الرابع عشر من شهر رمضان المعظم ... سنة 936 على ىد فقىر رحمة ربه بکم عبد الرحمن احمد بن محمد بن احمد ابن مجد الدىن [؟] المالکي لطف الله تعالى به وغفرله ولوالدىه ولمشاىخه ولاخوانه ولاصحابه ولجمىع المسلمىن اجمعىن امىن وحسبنا الله ونعم الوکىل وصلى الله على سىدنا محمد واله وصحبه وسلم

Marginal notes and glosses; ruled marginal lines in indigo. The title page is elaborately illuminated with gold and color. On several folios before the title page is the table of contents of the first volume. On two folios before the first in the second volume is a table of its contents. The edges are trimmed. The work is also known as al-Muḥīṭ al-Raḍawī. MS in good condition; Arabic leather binding with flap; blind stamped and tooling on cover and flap. In cases bearing title.
ḥājjī Khalīfah, Kashf al-ẓunūn (1835-58), V, p. 433; A catalogue of the Arabic manuscripts in the Library of the India Office, 206/7.

notes_index: A poem of religious contents, concerning the Islamic tradition in general and that relating to the Prophet in particular. The poem is a re-working in Ottoman verse by the author of the second part of his prose work in Arabic entitled Maghārib al-zamān.
Copied by Mustafa bin Salih bin Mustafa al-Egribozî [i.e. "the Negropontian"], known as Selim ... [?] and completed in Ṣafar 1167 (1753)) -- colophon (fol. 313a).

15 lines per page. Written in a medium small fully vocalised naskh in black ink with use of red for rubrication. Text is written in two columns inside a frame in gold leaf outlined in black ink, with columns and breaks also separated with lines in gold leaf. Fol. 1b has an illuminated head piece executed in gold leaf with red, blue, white, orange and pink watercolors. Catchwords on the verso of each leaf. Glazed European paper with watermarks. Foliation in Arabic numerals in black ink, starting with 2 on fol. 1a.
Verzeichnis der Orientalischen Handschriften in Deutschland, XIII, 2 (10).
GHB Sarajevo, Katalog arapskih, turskih, perzijskih i bosanskih rukopisa, v. 3 (2321).

Brown leather over pasteboard with envelope flap. Gold guilloche and fillets around edges of covers. Central mandorlas with pendants on upper and lower covers, blind stamped and painted with gold and brown. Pastedowns and lining to the envelope flap in green marbled paper. Lining to the fore edge flap in dark blue fabric.

cjk_all: Сальников, Алексей, 1978- author. Опосредованно : роман / Алексей Сальников. Москва : Редакция Елены Шубиной : Издательство АСТ, [2019] Классное чтение "Литературно-художественное издание"--Colophon. "В новом романе 'Опосредованно' представлена альтернативная реальность, где стихи - это не просто текст, а настоящий наркотик.Девушка Лена сочиняет свое первое стихотворение в семнадцать лет, чтобы получить одобрение старшего брата лучшей подруги. А потом не может бросить. Стишки становятся для нее и горем, и утешением, и способом заработать, и колдовством, и частью быта - ближе родных и друзей. Они не уходят, их не выкинешь, от них не отвяжешься, наверно потому, что кровь не водица, но все же отчасти - чернила.Цитаты из книги'Где бы ни родилась Лена, не подсесть на стишки ей стоило бы огромного труда. Из романов она почерпнула только, какие бывают виды прихода, а именно: скалам - восходящий и нисходящий, в зависимости от возникшего восторга; будда, превращающий голову в спокойного наблюдателя; ривер, делающий так, что мир втекает в тебя, как воздух; и тауматроп, совмещающий речь и ее изнанку в одну притягательную картину'.'Вот есть театр, есть кино, есть литература, есть стишки, которые не искусство вовсе, а просто умение копнуть в себе поглубже, так я понимаю, попытка понять и выразить словом то, как ощущает себя не разум, но психика, как она входящие сигналы принимает, как она себе представляет, то, что вокруг творится'."-- Provided by publisher. Классное чтение (Редакция Елены Шубиной)

notes_index: 880-06 "V novom romane 'Oposredovanno' predstavlena alʹternativnai︠a︡ realʹnostʹ, gde stikhi - ėto ne prosto tekst, a nastoi︠a︡shchiĭ narkotik.Devushka Lena sochini︠a︡et svoe pervoe stikhotvorenie v semnadt︠s︡atʹ let, chtoby poluchitʹ odobrenie starshego brata luchsheĭ podrugi. A potom ne mozhet brositʹ. Stishki stanovi︠a︡tsi︠a︡ dli︠a︡ nee i gorem, i utesheniem, i sposobom zarabotatʹ, i koldovstvom, i chastʹi︠u︡ byta - blizhe rodnykh i druzeĭ. Oni ne ukhodi︠a︡t, ikh ne vykineshʹ, ot nikh ne otvi︠a︡zheshʹsi︠a︡, naverno potomu, chto krovʹ ne vodit︠s︡a, no vse zhe otchasti - chernila.T︠S︡itaty iz knigi'Gde by ni rodilasʹ Lena, ne podsestʹ na stishki eĭ stoilo by ogromnogo truda. Iz romanov ona pocherpnula tolʹko, kakie byvai︠u︡t vidy prikhoda, a imenno: skalam - voskhodi︠a︡shchiĭ i niskhodi︠a︡shchiĭ, v zavisimosti ot voznikshego vostorga; budda, prevrashchai︠u︡shchiĭ golovu v spokoĭnogo nabli︠u︡dateli︠a︡; river, delai︠u︡shchiĭ tak, chto mir vtekaet v tebi︠a︡, kak vozdukh; i taumatrop, sovmeshchai︠u︡shchiĭ rechʹ i ee iznanku v odnu priti︠a︡gatelʹnui︠u︡ kartinu'.'Vot estʹ teatr, estʹ kino, estʹ literatura, estʹ stishki, kotorye ne iskusstvo vovse, a prosto umenie kopnutʹ v sebe poglubzhe, tak i︠a︡ ponimai︠u︡, popytka poni︠a︡tʹ i vyrazitʹ slovom to, kak oshchushchaet sebi︠a︡ ne razum, no psikhika, kak ona vkhodi︠a︡shchie signaly prinimaet, kak ona sebe predstavli︠a︡et, to, chto vokrug tvoritsi︠a︡'."-- Provided by publisher.

notes_index: Physical description: 15 lines per page; written in naskh in black on daluang paper. Text framed in triple black lines. Sūrah headings in red; āyahs marked by red circles and ajzāʾ marked by three red circles plus the number written in the margin. Opening pages (fol. 3b-4a), somewhat smudged, illuminated with simple geometric designs in red, green, and occasional gold. Closing pages (fol. 304b-305a) illuminated with geometric borders in black and red. Paginated in Arabic script by a later hand up to fol. 53a. Some staining and smudging; otherwise in good condition.
Copy of the Qurʾān from Sumatra or Java, likely 19th century.
Red leather over pasted boards; with painted designs, barely visible. Daluang paper pastedowns.

The Aboriginal Peoples Survey collected data on Aboriginal people 6 years of age and over (First Nations people living off reserve, Métis and Inuit) in urban, rural and northern locations throughout Canada. Although people living on reserve were not included in the provinces, all First Nations people, Métis and Inuit living in the territories were included.

notes_index: Commentary on Talkhīṣ al-Miftāḥ by Jalāl al-Dīn al-Qazwīnī (d. 739/1338), an abridgment of part 3 of Miftāḥ al-ʻulūm by al-Sakkākī (d. 626/1229), on al-Maʻānī wa-al-bayān. This copy has several ḥāshiyah on the margins and between the lines of the main text. On fol. 3a are short texts written so as to create several circles. The text is followed on fol. 107b by a short text by a later hand.

Physical description: 25 lines per page. Written in small taʻlīq in black ink with use of red. The text is framed within a single red line or a double red line, up to fol. 87a. The ḥāshiyah is framed within a single red line on some leaves. Ḥāshiyah written so as to create a geometrical or vegetal motif on fol. 17a-21a, with gold. Light cream paper, glossy, with laid and chain lines visible. Fol. 1-2 are later additions on European paper. Several ḥāshiyah on the margins, apparently by the same hand as the main text. Inscription in Arabic script mentioning the price of the ms. on fol. 1a. Inscription mentioning several dates on the upper corner of fol. 3a.
Inscription in Arabic script on a label pasted on the upper cover: "Lisān 7". Inscription in Arabic script on a label pasted on the pastedown of the upper cover: "Ḥāʼ 976".
Origin: Copy completed on Yawm al-khamīs 25 Shaʻbān 889 [Sept. 17, 1484] (colophon, fol. 174a).
From the books of Aḥmad Najīb ibn Aḥmad Ṭāhir (ownership statement dated 1279 H. on fol. 2a). Acquired from Abraham Shalom Yahuda, 1942.

Brown leather over paper pasteboards for upper and lower covers. Both covers have a gold stamped and brown-painted central mandorla with two pendants on the vertical axis, and an outer border consisting of gilt fillets and guilloche. Red brown leather doublure with a gilt fillet border and a central interlace motif forming a square on its pointe on a vertical chain. Later added fly-leaf, with one side in glossy dark magenta.
Brockelmann, C. GAL, I, 295 (Auszüge aus dem 3. Teil 1/Cmtare 4A) ; SI

880-05 Kim Sang-gyŏng, Mun Chŏng-hŭi, Ch'ae Chŏng-an, Mun Ta-in, Cho Chae-yun, Pang Min-a.

"The story starts with A-young Chae, who came up with an idea of a rental business of her own father. On the day of her school garage sale, A-young presents her father Taeman Chae, claiming that he is her useful item which is not in use, and JT, who craves for a father figure in his life, takes the offer and rents Taeman. Since then, A-young's puts an advertisement on a website and Taeman's father rental business expands making it official. However, out of shame, Taeman carries on his business without letting his wife, Jisu know about it. Taeman plays an excellent father figure for others who pay for the service, while neglecting his real family due to his busy schedule. Meanwhile, Jisu suspects Taeman's double life and figures he is having an affair with JT's mother, thus making their marriage fall apart. Realizing the crisis upon her family, A-young pays all her savings to rent her own father, Taeman. Taeman and Jisu realizes they have not paid enough attention to their daughter and reclaims their family value once and for all."--Korean Movie Database (KMDb).

notes_index: Commentary on al-ʻAqāʼid by ʻAḍud al-Dīn ʻAbd al-Raḥmān ibn Aḥmad al-Ījī (d. 756/1355).

16 lines per page. Written in thick shikastah nastaʻlīq in black ink with use of red. European glazed paper with watermark. Several ḥāshiyah (from the author, Maḥmūd Ḥasan, etc.) on the margins and on later pieces of paper pasted between the original folios. Inscriptions, including ownership statements on the pastedown of the upper cover and on fol. 1a. On fol. 1b-2a: Several short excerpts (one on the definition of mutakallimūn, ṣūfīyah, falāsifah, and ishrāqiyūn). On fol. 76a-b: Short excerpts and inscriptions. Modern foliation in pencil using Western numerals.
Inscription in Arabic script on a modern label pasted on the upper cover: "ʻAqāʼid 59". Inscription in Arabic script on a modern label pasted on the pastedown of the upper cover: "1274/2 Ḥāʼ".
Copied by Muṣṭafá ibn al-Ḥājjī Aḥmad ibn ʻAlī in Qayṣarīyah (madrasah Malik [...?]) in 1087 H. (colophon, fol. 75b).
Ownership statements (one dated 1286 H.) on the pastedown of the upper cover and on fol. 1a. Acquired from Abraham Shalom Yahuda, 1942.

"This hugely popular textbook has established itself as the topically organized textbook teachers and researchers trust for the most up-to-date perspectives on child and adolescent development. The authors, each a well-known scientist and educator, have earned that trust by introducing core concepts and impactful discoveries with an unparalleled integration of theory, cultural research, and applications. All this is delivered in a style that is authoritative yet immediately understandable and relevant." -- provided by publisher.

Questo libro riguarda la memoria delle Guerre persiane ad Atene, in rapporto con lo scenario panellenico, dall'immediato dopo Maratona fino alla cosiddetta 'prima Guerra del Peloponneso' (461?446). Esso analizza tutte le forme di memoria pre-storiografiche (poesia, iscrizioni, monumenti, topografia, teatro, riti, culti, festival, discorso pubblico) attraverso le quali le Guerre persiane vennero ricordate e rappresentate prima che Erodoto le raccontasse in forma storiografica.0Andando a riempire una lacuna nella ricerca attuale, il libro prende le mosse dalla consapevolezza per cui le Guerre persiane così come sono raccontate nelle Storie di Erodoto non corrispondono esattamente alla storia fattuale, ma sono invece l'esito di un processo multiforme e stratificato di memorializzazione, che decennio dopo decennio ha riplasmato gli eventi alla luce delle esigenze presenti. Combinando un approccio filologico alla documentazione letteraria, epigrafica e archeologica con un panorama teorico e metodologico influenzato dall'antropologia culturale e dagli studi sulla memoria, esso ricostruisce le immagini e i significati associati a ciascuno strato di tale processo, offrendo così una sorta di 'stratigrafia della memoria' delle Guerre persiane prima di Erodoto.

"The first in-depth exploration of the artistic and cultural achievements of China's "classical" era Age of Empires presents the art and culture of China during one of the most critical periods of its history - the four centuries from 221 B.C. to A.D. 200-- when, for the first time, people of diverse backgrounds were brought together under centralized imperial rule that fostered a new and unified identity. The Qin and Han empires represent the "classical" era of Chinese civilization, coinciding in both importance and timing with the Greco-Roman period in the West. Under the short-lived Qin and centuries-long Han, warring principalities were united under a common emperor, creating not only political and intellectual institutions but also the foundation for a Chinese art, culture, and national identity that lasted over two millennia. Over 150 works from across the full breadth of Chinese artistic and decorative media-- including ceramics, metalwork, textiles, armor, sculpture, and jewelry - are featured in this book and attest to the unprecedented role of art in ancient Chinese culture. These stunning objects, among them soldiers from the renowned terracotta army of Qin Shihuang, China's first emperor, are drawn from institutions and collections in China and appear here together for the first time. Essays by leading scholars, accompanied by dazzling new photography of the objects, address the sweeping societal changes underway, and trace a progression from the early, formative years through unprecedented sophistication and technical accomplishment--embodied in an artistic legacy that reverberates in China's national identity to this day"-- Provided by publisher.

"Age of Empires presents the art and culture of China during one of the most critical periods of its history - the four centuries from 221 B.C. to A.D. 200-- when, for the first time, people of diverse backgrounds were brought together under centralized imperial rule that fostered a new and unified identity. The Qin and Han empires represent the "classical" era of Chinese civilization, coinciding in both importance and timing with the Greco-Roman period in the West. Under the short-lived Qin and centuries-long Han, warring principalities were united under a common emperor, creating not only political and intellectual institutions but also the foundation for a Chinese art, culture, and national identity that lasted over two millennia. Over 150 works from across the full breadth of Chinese artistic and decorative media-- including ceramics, metalwork, textiles, armor, sculpture, and jewelry - are featured in this book and attest to the unprecedented role of art in ancient Chinese culture. These stunning objects, among them soldiers from the renowned terracotta army of Qin Shihuang, China's first emperor, are drawn from institutions and collections in China and appear here together for the first time"-- Provided by publisher.
